inference:
The equation $|z - 1| = |z + 3|$ says that $z$ is equidistant from 1 and $-3.$  Hence, $z$ lies on the perpendicular bisector of the segment connecting 1 and $-3.$  This perpendicular bisector is the line $x = -1.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.8 cm);

pair A, B, C, Z;

A = (1,0);
B = (-3,0);
C = (-1,0);
Z = intersectionpoint(arc(A,sqrt(20),0,360),arc(B,sqrt(20),0,360));

draw((-4,0)--(2,0));
draw((0,-2)--(0,2));
draw(Circle(A,sqrt(20)));
draw(Circle(B,sqrt(20)));
draw(Circle(C,sqrt(5)));
draw(rightanglemark(A,C,Z,20));

dot("$1$", A, SE);
dot("$-3$", B, SW);
dot("$z$", Z, NE);
[/asy]

The equation $|z - 1| = |z - i|$ says that $z$ is equidistant from 1 and $i.$  Hence, $z$ lies on the perpendicular bisector of the segment connecting 1 and $i.$  This perpendicular bisector is the line $x + y = 1.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.8 cm);

pair A, B, C, Z;

A = (1,0);
B = (-3,0);
C = (-1,0);
Z = intersectionpoint(arc(A,sqrt(20),0,360),arc(B,sqrt(20),0,360));

draw((-4,0)--(2,0));
draw((0,-2)--(0,2));
draw(Circle(A,sqrt(20)));
draw(Circle(B,sqrt(20)));
draw(Circle(C,sqrt(5)));
draw(rightanglemark(A,C,Z,20));
draw((-1,-2)--(-1,2),dashed);
draw((-2,3)--(2,-1));

dot("$1$", A, SE);
dot("$-3$", B, SW);
dot("$z$", Z, NE);
dot("$i$", (0,1), NW);
[/asy]

The intersection of the lines $x = -1$ and $x + y = 1$ is $(-1,2),$ so $z = \boxed{-1 + 2i}.$

